One of the most important aspects of good machine learning models is the representation of data in a form which is suitable for the algorithm. In the chemical sciences this often means representing atomic species by discrete representations such as atomic number, or by using one-hot channels for each unique atomic species, neither of which are ideal solutions. In this work we derive a continuous vector representation by compressing properties of each element with an auto-encoder, which captures underlying physical law and provides many advantages to several neural network models shown here.